        "content": "<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Ne</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">mul</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">@</span><span class=\"n\">mul_ne_zero</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">ha</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≠</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">hb</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≠</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≠</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ha</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">mul</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">hb</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I thought this was kind of cool, is it something mathlib would like? It was the first proof I tried before using <code>exact?</code>.</p>",
        "id": 520690916,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1748358225
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Assuming it goes in and people want to keep <code>mul_ne_zero</code> does this then automatically end up on Jovan's list of duplicated lemmas?</p>",
        "id": 520691123,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1748358271
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You could use <code>alias</code> and then it would be easier to auto-exclude from any automation</p>",
        "id": 520691843,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1748358457
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In general, we are happy to include aliases to support dot notation (\"generalized projection notation\"). The fact that this one doesn't mention <code>zero</code> irks me a bit, but I think this might be nice to have.</p>",
        "id": 520692205,
        "sender_full_name": "Floris van Doorn",
        "timestamp": 1748358547
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You could do this for <code>Ne.add</code> too. (There is <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=add_ne_zero#doc\">docs#add_ne_zero</a>, but it's not what I expected. Something with <code>[AddZeroClass α] [PartialOrder α] [CanonicallyOrderedAdd α]</code> probably.)</p>",
        "id": 520698808,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Meiburg",
        "timestamp": 1748360310
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yeah I agree that it not mentioning zero is a bit weird. But \"a not something\" and \"b not something\" implies \"a*b not something\" isn't going to have too many applications other than 0 (which is pretty common).</p>",
        "id": 520704354,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1748361882
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=ENNReal.mul_ne_top#doc\">docs#ENNReal.mul_ne_top</a> comes to mind, but probably shows up less in (the non-analysis part of) FLT than in Carleson :-)</p>",
        "id": 520706383,
        "sender_full_name": "Floris van Doorn",
        "timestamp": 1748362540
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh that's a good find! Is <code>Ne.mul\\_0</code> a better name then?</p>",
        "id": 520726717,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1748366645
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But isn't <code>Ne.mul</code> <code>a ≠ b -&gt; c ≠ d -&gt; a * c ≠ b * d</code>?</p>",
        "id": 520820987,
        "sender_full_name": "Jz Pan",
        "timestamp": 1748416860
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Of course it's not correct in general</p>",
        "id": 520821021,
        "sender_full_name": "Jz Pan",
        "timestamp": 1748416878
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's why it doesn't need the name :)</p>",
        "id": 520824255,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1748418130
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think \"not correct in general\" is a bit of an understatement\" :-)</p>",
        "id": 520834493,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1748421436
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110038\">Kevin Buzzard</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Ne.2Emul/near/520691123\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Assuming it goes in and people want to keep <code>mul_ne_zero</code> does this then automatically end up on Jovan's list of duplicated lemmas?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>As <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"310045\">@Eric Wieser</span> said, If you use <code>alias</code>, on won't appear on the list of duplicate lemmas.</p>",
